				</td>
				<td valign="bottom" style="width:01.00%;border-top:2pt double #000000 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;padding:0pt;">
					<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
						&nbsp;</p>
				</td>

					<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

		<p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Courier New;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;">NATIONAL PRESTO INDUSTRIES, INC. AND SUBSIDIARIES</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Courier New;font-size: 10pt">
			<a name="NotesToConsolidatedFinancialStatements"></a><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;">NOTES TO</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;"> CONDENSED</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;"> CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">(Unaudited)</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;text-decoration:underline;">NOTE A &#x2013; BASIS OF PRESENTATION</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The consolidated interim financial statements included herein are unaudited and have been prepared by the Company pursuant to the rules and regulations of the United States Securities and Exchange Commission (&#x201C;SEC&#x201D;). In the opinion of management of the Company, the consolidated interim financial statements reflect all the adjustments which were of a normal recurring nature necessary for a fair presentation of the results of the interim periods.&nbsp;&nbsp;The condensed consolidated balance sheet as of December 31, 201</font><font style="display: inline;">8</font><font style="display: inline;"> is summarized from audited consolidated financial statements, but does not include all the disclosures contained therein and should be read in conjunction with the 201</font><font style="display: inline;">8</font><font style="display: inline;"> Annual Report on Form 10-K</font><font style="display: inline;">/A</font><font style="display: inline;">.&nbsp;&nbsp;Interim results for the period are not indicative of those for the year.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">On January 3, 2017, the Company and its wholly-owned subsidiary, Presto Absorbent Products, Inc. (&#x201C;PAPI&#x201D;), entered into an asset purchase agreement wherein substantially all PAPI assets were sold and certain liabilities were assigned to Drylock Technologies, LTD. (&#x201C;Drylock&#x201D;) in exchange for </font><font style="display: inline;">$68,448,000</font><font style="display: inline;">.&nbsp;&nbsp;The asset purchase agreement also provided for additional proceeds of </font><font style="display: inline;">$4,000,000</font><font style="display: inline;"> upon the sale of certain delayed assets, consisting of machinery and equipment that were the subject of an involuntary conversion. The sale of the delayed assets was consummated during the second quarter of 2018 and resulted in </font><font style="display: inline;">no</font><font style="display: inline;"> gain or loss.&nbsp;&nbsp;As a result of </font><font style="display: inline;">aforementioned</font><font style="display: inline;"> transaction</font><font style="display: inline;">s</font><font style="display: inline;">, the Company classified its results of operations for all periods presented to reflect its Absorbent Products business as a discontinued operation and classified the assets and liabilities of its Absorbent Products business as held for sale.&nbsp;&nbsp;See Note </font><font style="display: inline;">K</font><font style="display: inline;"> for further discussion.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;text-decoration:underline;">NOTE B &#x2013; RECLASSIFICATIONS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">C</font><font style="display: inline;">ertain reclassifications have been made to the prior periods&#x2019; financial statements to conform to the current period&#x2019;s financial statement presentation.&nbsp;&nbsp;These reclassifications did not affect net earnings or stockholders&#x2019; equity as previously reported.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;text-decoration:underline;">NOTE C &#x2013; REVENUES</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The Company&#x2019;s revenues are derived from short-term contracts and programs that are typically completed within </font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">3</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to </font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">24</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> months and are recognized in accordance with ASC Topic 606, </font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Revenue from Contracts with Customers</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">. The Company&#x2019;s contracts each contain </font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">one</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> or more performance obligations: the physical delivery of distinct ordered product or products.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company provides an assurance type product warranty on its products to the original owner.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, for the Housewares/Small Appliances segment, the Company estimates returns of seasonal products and returns of newly introduced products sold with a return privilege.&nbsp;&nbsp;Stand-alone selling prices are set forth in each contract and are used to allocate revenue to the corresponding performance obligations.&nbsp;&nbsp;For the Housewares/Small Appliances segment, contracts include variable consideration, as the prices are subject to customer allowances, which principally consist of allowances for cooperative advertising, defective product, and trade discounts.&nbsp;&nbsp;Customer allowances are generally allocated to the performance obligations based on budgeted rates agreed upon with customers, as well as historical experience, and yield the Company&#x2019;s best estimate of the expected value for the variable consideration.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The Company's contracts in the Defense segment are primarily with the U.S. Department of Defense (DOD) and DOD prime contractors. As a consequence, this segment's business essentially depends on the product needs and governmental funding of the DOD. Substantially all of the work performed by the Defense segment directly or indirectly for the DOD is performed on a fixed-price basis. Under fixed-price contracts, the price paid to the contractor is awarded based on competition at the outset of the contract and therefore, with the exception of limited escalation provisions on specific materials, is generally not subject to any adjustments reflecting the actual costs incurred by the contractor.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">For the Housewares/Small Appliance segment, revenue is generally recognized as the completed, ordered product is shipped to the customer from the Company&#x2019;s warehouses.&nbsp;&nbsp;For the relatively few situations in which revenue should be recognized when product is received by the customer, the Company adjusts revenue accordingly.&nbsp;&nbsp;For the Defense segment, revenue is </font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">primarily </font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">recognized when the customer has legal title and formally documents that it has accepted the products.&nbsp; </font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">There are also certain termination clauses in Defense segment contracts that may give rise to the recognition of revenue</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, $9,412,000 of which was recognized during the third quarter of 2019</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">.&nbsp; </font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">In some situations, the customer may obtain legal title and accept the products at the Company&#x2019;s facilities, arranging for transportation at a later date, typically in </font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">one</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to </font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">four</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> weeks.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company does not consider the short-term storage of the customer owned products to be a material performance obligation, and no part of the transaction price is allocated to it.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			<font style="display: inline;"></font><font style="display: inline;">10</font><font style="display: inline;"></font>

		</p>

</div><hr size="3" style="color:#999999" width="100%" align="center"></hr><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Arial;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt;text-align:right;font-family:Arial;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

</div>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The timing of revenue recognition, billings, and cash collections results in billed accounts receivable, and customer advances and deposits (contract liabilities) on the Company&#x2019;s Condensed Consolidated Balance Sheets. For the Defense segment, the Company occasionally receives advances or deposits from certain customers before revenue is recognized, resulting in contract liabilities.&nbsp;&nbsp;These advances or deposits do not represent a significant financing component.&nbsp;&nbsp;As of </font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">September</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">29</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, 201</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">9 and December 31, 2018</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, &nbsp;</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">4</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">,</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">294</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">,000</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> and </font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">9</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">,</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">579</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">,000</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, respectively, of contract liabilities were included in Accounts Payable on the Company&#x2019;s Condensed Consolidated Balance Sheets.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company recognized revenue of </font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">9</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">,</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">574</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">nine</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">-month period ended </font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">September</font><font beginning of that period. The Company monitors its estimates of variable consideration, which includes customer allowances for cooperative advertising, defective product, and trade discounts, and returns of seasonal and newly introduced product, all of which pertain to the Housewares/Small Appliances segment, and periodically makes cumulative adjustments to the carrying amounts of these contract liabilities as appropriate.&nbsp;&nbsp;During the three</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> and </font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">nine</font><font estimates during the same periods.&nbsp; </font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">There were performance obligations satisfied in a previous period.&nbsp;&nbsp;The portion of contract transaction prices allocated to unsatisfied performance obligations, also known as the contract backlog, in the Company&#x2019;s Defense segment were </font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: unsatisfied performance obligations will be fulfilled in an </font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: Housewares/Small Appliances segment have original expected durations of less than one year. </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The Company&#x2019;s principal sources of revenue are derived from </font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">three</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> segme</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">nts: Housewares/Small Appliance, </font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Defense</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, and Safety</font><font style="font-family:TimesNewRoman;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;color:#000000;font-size:12pt;display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, as shown in Note E. Management utilizes the performance measures by segment to evaluate the financial performance of and make operating decisions for the Company.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;text-decoration:underline;">NOTE D &#x2013; EARNINGS PER SHARE</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Basic earnings per share is based on the weighted average number of common shares and participating securities outstanding during the period.&nbsp;&nbsp;Diluted earnings per share also includes the dilutive effect of additional potential common shares issuable.&nbsp;&nbsp;Unvested stock awards, which contain non-forfeitable rights to dividends whether paid or unpaid (&#x201C;participating securities&#x201D;), are included in the number of shares outstanding for both basic and diluted earnings per share calculations.&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;text-decoration:underline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;text-decoration:underline;">NOTE E &#x2013; BUSINESS SEGMENTS</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">In the following summary, operating profit represents earnings before other income and income taxes.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company's segments operate discretely from each other with no shared</font><font style="display: inline;"> owned or leased</font><font style="display: inline;"> manufacturing facilities.&nbsp;&nbsp;Costs associated with corporate activities (such as cash and marketable securities management) and the assets associated with such activities are included within the Housewares/Small Appliances segment for all periods presented.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			<font style="display: inline;"></font><font style="display: inline;">11</font><font style="display: inline;"></font>

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;"></font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">On July 23, 2019, the Company purchased substantially all the assets of OneEvent Technologies, Inc., a Mount Horeb, Wisconsin company established in 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;OneEvent&#x2019;s cloud-based learning and analytics engine utilizes a series of sensing devices integrated with a cellular gateway to predict, alert, and prevent.&nbsp;&nbsp;Sensors measure a variety of environmental data including smoke, temperature, carbon monoxide, humidity, water, motion, and more.&nbsp;&nbsp;See Note</font><font style="display: inline;"> L.&nbsp;&nbsp;Because a</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">major</font><font style="display: inline;"> focus of OneEvent is fire protection for buildings, homes, assets, and occupant, the Company has created a new operating segment, &#x201C;Safety,&#x201D; combining its operations with those of Rusoh, Inc., which designs and markets fire extinguishers.&nbsp;&nbsp;Previously, Rusoh, Inc. had been included in the Company&#x2019;s Housewares/Small Appliance segment.&nbsp;&nbsp;Prior period segment information has been restated to reflect the Company&#x2019;s current segmentation.</font>
		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt">

		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;text-decoration:underline;">NOTE F - FAIR VALUE OF FINANCIAL INSTRUMENTS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Company utilizes the methods of fair value as described in Financial Accounting Standard Board (&#x201C;FASB&#x201D;) Accounting Standard Codification (&#x201C;ASC&#x201D;) 820, </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Fair Value Measurements and Disclosures,</font><font style="display: inline;"> to value its financial assets and liabilities. ASC 820 utilizes a three-tier fair value hierarchy which prioritizes the inputs used in measuring fair value. These tiers include: Level 1, defined as observable inputs such as quoted prices in active markets; Level 2, defined as inputs other than quoted prices in active markets that are either directly or indirectly observable; and Level 3, defined as unobservable inputs in which little or no market data exists, therefore requiring an entity to develop its own assumptions.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The carrying amounts for cash and cash equivalents, accounts receivable, notes receivable, accounts payable, and accrued liabilities approximate fair value due to the immediate or short-term maturity of these financial instruments.&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;text-decoration:underline;">NOTE G - CASH, CASH EQUIVALENTS AND MARKETABLE SECURITIES&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Company considers all highly liquid marketable securities with an original maturity of three months or less to be cash equivalents.&nbsp;&nbsp;Cash equivalents include money market funds.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company deposits its cash in high quality financial institutions.&nbsp;&nbsp;The balances, at times, may exceed federally insured limits.&nbsp;&nbsp;Money market funds are reported at fair value determined using quoted prices in active markets for identical securities (Level 1, as defined by FASB ASC 820).</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Company has classified all marketable securities as available-for-sale which requires the securities to be reported at estimated fair value, with unrealized gains and losses, net of tax, reported as a separate component of stockholders' equity.&nbsp;&nbsp;Highly liquid, tax-exempt variable rate demand notes with put options exercisable in three months or less are classified as marketable securities.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">At </font><font style="display: inline;">September 29</font><font style="display: inline;">, 201</font><font style="display: inline;">9 and December 31, 2018</font><font style="display: inline;">, cost for marketable securities was determined using the specific identification method.&nbsp;&nbsp;A summary of the amortized costs and fair values of the Company&#x2019;s marketable securities at the end of the periods presented is shown in the following table.&nbsp;&nbsp;All of the Company&#x2019;s marketable securities are classified as Level 2, as defined by FASB ASC 820, with fair values determined using significant other observable inputs, which include quoted prices in markets that are not active, quoted prices of similar securities, recently executed transactions, broker quotations, and oth</font><font style="display: inline;">er inputs that are observable.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;">The contractual maturities of the marketable securities held at</font><font style="display: inline;"> September</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">29</font><font style="display: inline;">, 201</font><font style="display: inline;">9</font><font style="display: inline;"> are as follows: </font><font style="display: inline;">$2</font><font style="display: inline;">9</font><font style="display: inline;">,</font><font style="display: inline;">913</font><font style="display: inline;">,000</font><font style="display: inline;"> within one year; $</font><font style="display: inline;">15</font><font style="display: inline;">,</font><font style="display: inline;">496</font><font style="display: inline;">,000</font><font style="display: inline;"> beyond one year to five years; $</font><font style="display: inline;">4,14</font><font style="display: inline;">6</font><font style="display: inline;">,000</font><font style="display: inline;"> beyond five years to ten years, and $</font><font style="display: inline;">3</font><font style="display: inline;">5</font><font style="display: inline;">,</font><font style="display: inline;">226</font><font style="display: inline;">,000</font><font style="display: inline;"> beyond ten years.</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> All </font><font style="display: inline;">of </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">the instruments in the beyond five year ranges are variable rate demand notes which can be tendered for cash at par plus </font><font style="display: inline;">interest </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">within </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">seven</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> days.&nbsp;&nbsp;Despite the stated contractual maturity date, to the extent a tender is not honored, the notes become </font><font style="display: inline;">immediately </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">due and payable.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;text-decoration:underline;">NOTE H &#x2013; OTHER ASSETS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Other Assets includes prepayments that are made from time to time by the Company for certain materials used in the manufacturing process in the Housewares/Small Appliances segment.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company expects to utilize the prepayments and related materials over an estimated period of </font><font style="display: inline;">two</font><font style="display: inline;"> years.&nbsp;&nbsp;As of </font><font style="display: inline;">September</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">29</font><font style="display: inline;">, 201</font><font style="display: inline;">9</font><font style="display: inline;"> and December 31, 201</font><font style="display: inline;">8</font><font style="display: inline;">, &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">$</font><font style="display: inline;">10</font><font style="display: inline;">,</font><font style="display: inline;">615</font><font style="display: inline;">,000</font><font style="display: inline;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;">$</font><font style="display: inline;">6</font><font style="display: inline;">,</font><font style="display: inline;">864</font><font style="display: inline;">,000</font><font style="display: inline;"> of such prepayments, respectively, remained unused and outstanding.&nbsp;&nbsp;At </font><font style="display: inline;">September</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">29</font><font style="display: inline;">, 201</font><font style="display: inline;">9 and December 31, 2018</font><font style="display: inline;">,</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">$4,</font><font style="display: inline;">0</font><font style="display: inline;">56</font><font style="display: inline;">,000</font><font style="display: inline;"> and</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">$</font><font style="display: inline;">5</font><font style="display: inline;">,</font><font style="display: inline;">19</font><font style="display: inline;">0,000</font><font style="display: inline;">, respectively were included</font><font style="display: inline;"> in Other Current Assets, representing the Company&#x2019;s best estimate of the expected utilization of the prepayments and related materials during the twelve-month periods following those dates.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;text-decoration:underline;">NOTE I &#x2013; LEASES</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Company accounts for leases under ASC </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Topic 842, Leases</font><font style="display: inline;">, which was adopted on January 1, 2019.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company&#x2019;s leasing activities include roles as both lessee and lessor.&nbsp;&nbsp;As lessee, the Company&#x2019;s primary leasing activities include buildings and structures to support its manufacturing operations at one location in its Defense segment, and warehouse space and equipment to support its distribution center operations in its Housewares/Small Appliances segment.&nbsp;&nbsp;As lessor, the Company&#x2019;s primary leasing activity is comprised of manufacturing and office space located adjacent to its corporate offices.&nbsp;&nbsp;All of the Company&#x2019;s leases are classified as operating leases.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Company&#x2019;s leases as lessee in its Defense segment provide for variable lease payments that are based on changes in the Consumer Price Index.&nbsp;&nbsp;As lessor, the Company&#x2019;s primary lease also provides for variable lease payments that are based on changes in the Consumer Price Index, as well as on increases in costs of insurance, real estate taxes, and utilities related to the leased space. Generally, all of the Company&#x2019;s lease contracts provide for options to extend and terminate them.</font><font style="display: inline;"> &nbsp;The majority of lease terms of the Company&#x2019;s </font><font style="display: inline;">lease</font><font style="display: inline;"> contracts </font><font style="display: inline;">reflect</font><font style="display: inline;"> extension options</font><font style="display: inline;">, while none reflect termination options</font><font style="display: inline;">. &nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Company has determined that the rates implicit in its leases are not readily determinable and estimates its incremental borrowing rates utilizing quotes from financial institutions for real estate and equipment, as applicable, over periods of time similar to the terms of its leases. The Company has entered into various short-term leases as lessee and has elected a non-recognition accounting policy, as permitted by ASC </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Topic 842</font><font style="display: inline;">.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>

			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Company considers risk associated with the residual value of its leased real property to be low, given the nature of the long-term lease agreement, the Company&#x2019;s ability to control the maintenance of the property, and the creditworthiness of the lessee.&nbsp;&nbsp;The residual value risk is further mitigated by the long-lived nature of the property, and the propensity of such assets to hold their value or, in some cases, appreciate in value.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;text-decoration:underline;">NOTE </font><font style="display: inline;text-decoration:underline;">J</font><font style="display: inline;text-decoration:underline;"> &#x2013; COMMITMENTS AND CONTINGENCIES</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Company is involved in largely routine litigation incidental to its business.&nbsp;&nbsp;Management believes the ultimate outcome of the litigation will not have a material effect on the Company's consolidated financial position, liquidity, or results of operations.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;text-decoration:underline;">NOTE K &#x2013; DISCONTINUED OPERATIONS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">On January 3, 2017, the Company and its wholly-owned subsidiary, Presto Absorbent Products, Inc. (&#x201C;PAPI&#x201D;), entered into an asset purchase agreement wherein substantially all PAPI assets were sold and certain liabilities were assigned to Drylock Technologies, LTD. (&#x201C;Drylock&#x201D;) in exchange for </font><font style="display: inline;">$68,448,000</font><font style="display: inline;">. The asset purchase agreement also provided for additional proceeds of </font><font style="display: inline;">$4,000,000</font><font style="display: inline;"> upon the sale of certain delayed assets, consisting of machinery and equipment that were the subject of an involuntary conversion.&nbsp;&nbsp;The sale of the delayed assets was consummated during the second quarter of 2018 and resulted in </font><font style="display: inline;">no</font><font style="display: inline;"> gain or loss.&nbsp;&nbsp;As a result of the aforementioned transactions, the Company classified its results of operations for all periods presented to reflect its Absorbent Products business as a discontinued operation and classified the assets and liabilities of its Absorbent Products business as held for sale. The Company&#x2019;s pre-tax gain on sale of </font><font style="display: inline;">$11,413,000</font><font style="display: inline;">, net of one-time transaction costs, was recorded in 2017 within earnings from discontinued operations.&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Consolidated Statements of Cash Flows do not present the cash flows from discontinued operations separately from cash flows from continuing operations.&nbsp;&nbsp;Cash</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">used</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">in operating activities from discontinued operations was </font><font style="display: inline;">$1,050</font><font style="display: inline;">,000</font><font style="display: inline;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;">$</font><font style="display: inline;">562</font><font style="display: inline;">,000</font><font style="display: inline;"> for the nine</font><font style="display: inline;"> &nbsp;m</font><font style="display: inline;">onths ended September 29, 2019 and September</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">30</font><font style="display: inline;">, 2018, respectively. Cash provided by investing activities related to discontinued operations was </font><font style="display: inline;">$3,107</font><font style="display: inline;">,000</font><font style="display: inline;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;">$6,134,000</font><font style="display: inline;"> for the nine</font><font style="display: inline;"> months ended </font><font style="display: inline;">September</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">29, 2019 and September</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">30</font><font style="display: inline;">, 2018, respectively.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">In connection with the asset purchase agreement discussed above, the Company entered into a </font><font style="display: inline;">10</font><font style="display: inline;">-year lease agreement with Drylock for a portion of its manufacturing and warehouse facilities.&nbsp;&nbsp;The lease agreement provided for total annual payments of </font><font style="display: inline;">$1,288,000</font><font style="display: inline;"> initially. During the fourth quarter of 2018, the lease agreement was amended to incorporate additional facilities that the Company built for Drylock.&nbsp;&nbsp;The amended lease provides for an initial term of approximately </font><font style="display: inline;">14</font><font style="display: inline;"> years, and allows for successive </font><font style="display: inline;">three</font><font style="display: inline;">-year renewal periods, as well as options to terminate the lease early after </font><font style="display: inline;">five</font><font style="display: inline;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;">ten</font><font style="display: inline;"> years. The amended lease also provides for adjustments to the rental payments based on certain price indices, taxes, and space occupied. The Company estimates that annual payments under the</font><font style="display: inline;"> amended</font><font style="display: inline;"> lease will total </font><font style="display: inline;">$1,755,000</font><font style="display: inline;">.&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;">The amounts received from Drylock for rental income are recorded in Other Income on the Consolidated Statements of Comprehensive Income.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;text-decoration:underline;">NOTE L</font><font style="display: inline;text-decoration:underline;"> &#x2013; BUSINESS ACQUISITION</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">On </font><font style="display: inline;">July 23, 2019</font><font style="display: inline;">, the Company&#x2019;s wholly-owned subsidiary, OETA, Inc., purchased substantially all the assets of OneEvent Technologies, Inc., a Mount Horeb, Wisconsin company established in 2014</font><font style="display: inline;"> for </font><font style="display: inline;">$6,8</font><font style="display: inline;">5</font><font style="display: inline;">5,000</font><font style="display: inline;">, including</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">cash of </font><font style="display: inline;">$4,021,000</font><font style="display: inline;">, &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">forgiveness of a note receivable of </font><font style="display: inline;">$2,364,000</font><font style="display: inline;"> and</font><font style="display: inline;"> a potential earn out</font><font style="display: inline;">, which is based on earnings over a </font><font style="display: inline;">seven</font><font style="display: inline;"> year period.&nbsp;&nbsp;The current estimated value of the earn out</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">is</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">$470,000</font><font style="display: inline;">, however, the value of the earn out will vary depending on actual earni</font><font style="display: inline;">ngs </font><font style="display: inline;">over the</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">seven</font><font style="display: inline;"> year period</font><font style="display: inline;">. OneEvent&#x2019;s cloud-based learning and analytics engine utilizes a series of sensing devices integrated with a cellular gateway to predict, alert, and prevent.&nbsp;&nbsp;Sensors measure a variety of environmental data including smoke, temperature, carbon monoxide, humidity, water, motion and more.&nbsp;&nbsp;Pursuant to the terms of the transaction, the seller has subsequently changed its corporate name, and OETA, Inc. has now legally adopted the corporate name, OneEvent Technologies, Inc.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			<font style="display: inline;"></font><font style="display: inline;">16</font><font style="display: inline;"></font>

		</p>

</div><hr size="3" style="color:#999999" width="100%" align="center"></hr><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Arial;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt;text-align:right;font-family:Arial;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

</div>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;">The acquisition was accounted for under the acquisition method of accounting with the Company treated as the acquiring entity.&nbsp;&nbsp;Accordingly, the consideration paid by the Company to complete the acquisition </font><font style="display: inline;">has</font><font style="display: inline;"> been recorded to the assets acquired and liabilities assumed based upon their estimated fair values as of the date of acquisition.&nbsp;&nbsp;The carrying values for current assets and liabilities were deemed to approximate their fair values due to the short-term nature of these assets and liabilities.&nbsp;&nbsp;The following table shows the amounts recorded as of their acquisition date.&nbsp;&nbsp;These estimates are based on </font><font style="display: inline;">a</font><font style="display: inline;"> preliminary valuation</font><font style="display: inline;">, which the Company expects to finalize during the first quarter of 2020</font><font style="display: inline;">.</font>
		</p>

			<font style="display: inline;">The acquired intangibles primarily include technology software and patents</font><font style="display: inline;"> that will be amortized over a period of 10-15 years</font><font style="display: inline;">.&nbsp;&nbsp;The amount of goodwill recorded reflects expected synergies with the Company&#x2019;s other subsidiary in the Safety segment, Rusoh, Inc.&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;">The recorded goodwill is deductible for income tax purposes over a fifteen year period.&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;">The Company&#x2019;s results of operations for 2019 include revenue of </font><font style="display: inline;">$13,000</font><font style="display: inline;"> and loss of </font><font style="display: inline;">($298,000)</font><font style="display: inline;"> from the acquired facility from the date of acquisition through September 30, 2019.&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;">The following pro forma condensed consolidated results of operations has been prepared as if the acquisition had occurred as of January 1, 2018. </font>

			<font style="display: inline;text-decoration:underline;">NOTE </font><font style="display: inline;text-decoration:underline;">M</font><font style="display: inline;text-decoration:underline;"> &#x2013; RECENTLY ISSUED ACCOUNTING PRONOUNCEMENTS</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">In January 2017, the FASB issued ASU No. 2017-04, </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Intangibles - Goodwill and Other (Topic 350): Simplifying the Test for Goodwill Impairment</font><font style="display: inline;">, which eliminates the performance of Step 2 from the goodwill impairment test. In performing its annual or interim impairment testing, an entity will instead compare the fair value of the reporting unit with its carrying amount and recognize any impairment charge for the amount by which the carrying amount exceeds the reporting unit&#x2019;s fair value. Additionally, an entity should consider income tax effects from any tax deductible goodwill on the carrying amount of the reporting unit when measuring the goodwill impairment loss. The standard is effective for fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2019.&nbsp;&nbsp;Early adoption is permitted for interim or annual impairment tests performed on testing dates after January 1, 2017. The Company does not expect the adoption of ASU 2017-04 to have a material impact on its consolidated financial statements. </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">In June 2016, the FASB issued ASU No. 2016-13,</font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;"> Financial Instruments&#x2014;Credit Losses (Topic 326): Measurement of Credit Losses on Financial Instruments</font><font style="display: inline;">.&nbsp;&nbsp;ASU 2016-13 provides</font><font style="display: inline;"> guidance for estimating credit losses on certain types of financial instruments, including trade receivables, by introducing an approach based on expected losses. The expected loss approach will require entities to incorporate considerations of historical information, current information and reasonable and supportable forecasts. ASU 2016-13 also amends the accounting for credit losses on available-for-sale debt securities and purchased financial assets with credit deterioration.&nbsp;&nbsp;The guidance is effective for fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2019, including interim periods within those fiscal years. The guidance requires a modified retrospective transition method and early adoption is permitted. The Company is currently evaluating the impact of the adoption of ASU 2016-13 on its consolidated financial statements.</font>
		</p>

There are certain important factors that could cause results to differ materially from those anticipated by some of the statements made herein.&nbsp;&nbsp;Investors are cautioned that all forward-looking statements involve risks and uncertainty. In addition to the factors discussed herein and in the Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements, among the other factors that could cause actual results to differ materially are the following: consumer spending and debt levels; interest rates; continuity of relationships with and purchases by major customers; product mix; the benefit and risk of business acquisitions; competitive pressure on sales and pricing; development and market acceptance of new products; increases in material, freight/shipping, tariffs, or production cost which cannot be recouped in product pricing; delays or interruptions in shipping or production; reliance on third-party suppliers in Asia; shipment of defective product which could result in product liability claims or recalls; work or labor disruptions stemming from a unionized work force; changes in government requirements, military spending, and funding of government contracts, which could result in, among other things, the modification or termination of existing contracts; dependence on subcontractors or vendors to perform as required by contract; the efficient start-up and utilization of capital equipment investments; political actions of federal and state governments which could have an impact on everything from the value of the U.S dollar vis-&#xE0;-vis other currencies to the availability of affordable labor and energy; and information technology system failures or security breaches.&nbsp;&nbsp;Additional information concerning these and other factors is contained in the Company's Securities and Exchange Commission filings.</font>

			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Discontinued Operations</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">On January 3, 2017, the Company and its wholly-owned subsidiary, Presto Absorbent Products, Inc. (&#x201C;PAPI&#x201D;), entered into an asset purchase agreement wherein substantially all PAPI assets were sold and certain liabilities were assigned to Drylock Technologies, LTD. As a result of this transaction, the Company classified its results of operations for all periods presented to reflect its Absorbent Products business as a discontinued operation and classified the assets and liabilities of its Absorbent Products business as held for sale. The operations of PAPI previously comprised the Company&#x2019;s Absorbent Products segment.</font>

style="display: inline;background-color: #FFFFFF;">692</font><font style="display: inline;background-color: #FFFFFF;">,000 to $</font><font style="display: inline;background-color: #FFFFFF;">,0</font><font style="display: inline;">00, which resulted in an effective income tax rate of 21% in 2019 </font><font style="display: inline;">versus 22% in</font><font style="display: 		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

(&#x201C;PAPI&#x201D;), entered into an asset purchase agreement wherein substantially all PAPI assets were sold and certain liabilities were assigned to Drylock Technologies, LTD. As a result of this transaction, the Company classified its results of operations for all periods presented to reflect its Absorbent Products business as a discontinued operation and classified the assets and liabilities of its Absorbent Products busine</font><font style="display: inline;">ss as held for sale. 		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Company expects to continue to evaluate acquisition opportunities that align with its business segments and will make further acquisitions, as well as continue to make capital investments in these segments per existing authorized projects and for additional projects, if the appropriate return on investment is projected.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Company has substantial liquidity in the form of cash and cash equivalents and marketable securities to meet all of its anticipated capital requirements, to make dividend payments, and to fund future growth through acquisitions and other means.&nbsp;&nbsp;The bulk of its marketable securities are invested in the tax exempt </font><font style="display: inline;">variable rate demand notes described above and in fixed rate municipal notes and bonds.</font><font style="display: inline;"> The Company intends to continue its investment strategy of safety and short-term liquidity throughout its investment holdings. </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">Critical Accounting Policies </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The preparation of the Company&#x2019;s Consolidated Financial Statements in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States requires management to make certain estimates and assumptions that affect the amount of reported assets and liabilities and disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the Consolidated Financial Statements and revenues and expenses during the periods reported.&nbsp;&nbsp;Actual results may differ from those estimates.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company reviewed the development and selection of the critical accounting policies and believes the following are the most critical accounting policies that could have an effect on the Company&#x2019;s reported results.&nbsp;&nbsp;These critical accounting policies and estimates have been reviewed with the Audit Committee of the Board of Directors.&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			<font style="display: inline;"></font><font style="display: inline;">21</font><font style="display: inline;"></font>

		</p>

</div><hr size="3" style="color:#999999" width="100%" align="center"></hr><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Arial;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt;text-align:right;font-family:Arial;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

</div>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;text-decoration:underline;">Inventories</font><font style="display: inline;"> &nbsp; &nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">New Housewares/Small Appliance product introductions are an important part of the Company&#x2019;s sales to offset the morbidity rate of other Housewares/Small Appliance products and/or the effect of lowered acceptance of seasonal products due to weather conditions.&nbsp;&nbsp;New products entail unusual risks and have occasionally in the past resulted in losses related to obsolete or excess inventory as a result of low or diminishing demand for a product.&nbsp;&nbsp;There were no such obsolescence issues that had a material effect during the current period, and accordingly, the Company did not record a reserve for obsolete product.&nbsp;&nbsp;In the future should product demand issues arise, the Company may incur losses related to the obsolescence of the related inventory.&nbsp;&nbsp;Inventory risk for the Company&#x2019;s Defense segment is not deemed to be significant, as products are largely built pursuant to customers&#x2019; specific orders.&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;text-decoration:underline;">Self-Insured Product Liability and Health Insurance</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Company is subject to product liability claims in the normal course of business and is self-insured for health care costs, although it does carry stop loss and other insurance to cover claims once a health care claim reaches a specified threshold.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company&#x2019;s insurance coverage varies from policy year to policy year, and there are typically limits on all types of insurance coverage, which also vary from policy year to policy year.&nbsp;&nbsp;Accordingly, the Company records an accrual for known claims and incurred but not reported claims, including an estimate for related legal fees in the Company&#x2019;s Consolidated Financial Statements.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company utilizes historical trends and other analysis to assist in determining the appropriate accrual.&nbsp;&nbsp;There are no known claims that would have a material adverse impact on the Company beyond the reserve levels that have been accrued and recorded on the Company&#x2019;s books and records.&nbsp;&nbsp;An increase in the number or magnitude of claims could have a material impact on the Company&#x2019;s financial condition and results of operations.&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;text-decoration:underline;">Revenues</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Sales are recorded net of discounts and returns for the Housewares/Small Appliance segment.&nbsp;&nbsp;Sales discounts and returns are key aspects of variable consideration, which is a significant estimate utilized in revenue recognition.&nbsp;&nbsp;Sales returns pertain primarily to warranty returns, returns of seasonal items, and returns of those newly introduced products sold with a return privilege.&nbsp;&nbsp;The calculation of warranty returns is based in large part on historical data, while seasonal and new product returns are primarily developed using customer provided information.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;text-decoration:underline;">Impairment and Valuation of Long-lived Assets</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Company reviews long-lived assets for impairment whenever events or changes in circumstances indicate that the related carrying amounts may not be recoverable. Long-lived assets consist of property, plant and equipment and intangible assets, including the value of a government sales contract. Determining whether an impairment has occurred typically requires various estimates and assumptions, including determining which cash flows are directly related to the potentially impaired asset, the useful life over which cash flows will occur, the amounts of the cash flows and the asset&#x2019;s residual value, if any. In turn, measurement of an impairment loss requires a determination of fair value, which is based on the best information available. The Company uses internal discounted cash flows estimates, quoted market prices when available and independent appraisals, as appropriate, to determine fair value. The Company derives the required cash flow estimates from its historical experience and its internal business plans.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">ITEM 3</font><font style="display: inline;">.&nbsp; </font><a name="QuantitativeAndQualitativeDisclosuresAbo"></a><font style="display: inline;">QUANTITATIVE</font><font style="display: inline;"> AND QUALITATIVE DISCLOSURES ABOUT MARKET RISK</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Company's interest income on cash equivalents and marketable securities is affected by changes in interest rates in the United States.&nbsp;&nbsp;Cash equivalents primarily consist of money market funds. Based on the accounting profession&#x2019;s interpretation of cash equivalents under FASB ASC Topic 230, the Company&#x2019;s seven-day variable rate demand notes are classified as marketable securities rather than as cash equivalents.&nbsp;&nbsp;The demand notes are highly liquid instruments with interest rates set every seven days that can be tendered to the trustee or remarketer upon seven days notice for payment of principal and accrued interest amounts.&nbsp;&nbsp;The seven-day tender feature of these variable rate demand notes is further supported by an irrevocable letter of credit from highly rated U.S. banks.&nbsp;&nbsp;To the extent a bond is not remarketed at par plus accrued interest, the difference is drawn from the bank&#x2019;s letter of credit.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company has had no issues tendering these notes to the trustees or remarketers.&nbsp;&nbsp;Other than a failure of a major U.S. bank, there are no risks of which the Company is aware that relate to these notes in the current market. The balance of the Company&#x2019;s investments is held primarily in fixed and variable rate municipal bonds with a weighted average life of </font><font style="display: inline;">0</font><font style="display: inline;">.</font><font style="display: inline;">8</font><font style="display: inline;"> years.&nbsp;&nbsp;Accordingly, changes in interest rates have not had a material effect on the Company, and </font>
		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			<font style="display: inline;"></font><font style="display: inline;">22</font><font style="display: inline;"></font>

		</p>

</div><hr size="3" style="color:#999999" width="100%" align="center"></hr><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Arial;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt;text-align:right;font-family:Arial;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

</div>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;">the Company does not anticipate that future exposure to interest rate market risk will be material.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company uses sensitivity analysis to determine its exposure to changes in interest rates.&nbsp; </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Company has no history of, and does not anticipate in the future, investing in derivative financial instruments.&nbsp;&nbsp;Most transactions with international customers are entered into in U.S. dollars, precluding the need for foreign currency cash flow hedges. As the majority of the Housewares/Small Appliance segment&#x2019;s suppliers are located in China, periodic changes in the U.S. dollar and Chinese Renminbi (RMB) exchange rates do have an impact on that segment&#x2019;s product costs. It is anticipated that any potential material impact from fluctuations in the exchange rate will be to the cost of products secured via purchase orders issued subsequent to the revaluation.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">ITEM 4. </font><a name="ControlsAndProcedures"></a><font style="display: inline;">CONTROLS AND PROCEDURES</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Courier New;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;text-decoration:underline;">Evaluation of Disclosure Controls and Procedures</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Company&#x2019;s management, including the Chief Executive Officer and Treasurer (principal financial officer), conducted an evaluation of the effectiveness of the design and operation of the Company&#x2019;s disclosure controls and procedures pursuant to Rule 13a-15 under the Securities Exchange Act </font><font style="display: inline;">of 1934 (the &#x201C;1934 Act&#x201D;) as of September</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">29</font><font style="display: inline;">, 2019. The Company&#x2019;s Chief Executive Officer and Treasurer (principal financial officer) have concluded that the Company&#x2019;s disclosure controls and procedures were not effective as of </font><font style="display: inline;">September</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">29</font><font style="display: inline;">, 2019, as a result of a material weakness in internal control over financial reporting described below. </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Courier New;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;">A material weakness is a deficiency, or a combination of deficiencies, in internal control over financial reporting, such that there is a reasonable possibility that a material misstatement in the Company&#x2019;s annual or interim financial statements will not be prevented or detected on a timely basis. All internal control systems, no matter how well designed, have inherent limitations. Therefore, even those systems determined to be effective can provide only reasonable assurance with respect to financial statement preparation and presentation.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Courier New;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;">In Item 9A of the Company&#x2019;s Annual Report on Form 10-K/A for the year ended December 31, 2018 filed with the SEC on November 15, 2019, management identified a material weakness in its internal controls over financial reporting related to revenue recognition. The Company did not properly design and maintain effective controls over revenue for its Defense segment, as the controls failed to demonstrate an appropriate level of precision over the assessment and documentation of the point in time pattern of revenue recognition, and did not fully consider alternative use and the impact of certain termination clauses in its contracts with customers that might create a legal right for payment for work completed prior to the contract termination that would include a reasonable profit margin. </font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Courier New;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Courier New;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;">Notwithstanding the material weakness described above, the Company&#x2019;s management has concluded that the consolidated financial statem</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;">ents</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;"> included in this Form 10-Q, present fairly, in all material respects, the Company&#x2019;s financial position, results of operations and cash flow for the periods presented, in conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America (U.S. GAAP).</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Courier New;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Courier New;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;text-decoration:underline;">Remediation Plan</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Courier New;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">The Company has designed a remediation plan to address the control deficiencies and strengthen its internal control over financial reporting, which entails reassessing the design and operating effectiveness of its controls over the review of Defense segment contracts, including implementing an appropriate level of precision in its reviews to identify significant key terms and assumptions that could impact the pattern of revenue recognition.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Courier New;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;text-decoration:underline;">Changes in Internal Control over Financial Reporting</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Courier New;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;font-family:Times New Roman;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">Other than the material weakness described above, there were no changes in internal controls over financial repor</font><font style="display: inline;">ting during the quarter ended September</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">29</font><font style="display: inline;">, 2019 that have materially affected, or are reasonably likely to materially affect, the Company&#x2019;s internal control over financial reporting.</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
			<font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font>
		</p>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

		</p>
		<p><font size="1"> </font></p><div style="width:100%">

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">

			<font style="display: inline;"></font><font style="display: inline;">23</font><font style="display: inline;"></font>

		</p>

			&nbsp;

		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt;text-align:right;font-family:Arial;font-size: 10pt">

			&nbsp;

		</p>

</div>
		<p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;"></font><font style="display: inline;">PART II - </font><a name="OtherInformation"></a><font style="display: inline;">OTHER INFORMATION</font>
		</p>

		<p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt">
